{"id":14881230,"mediaExerciseId":"529eec08-9efd-482f-bd73-0357d37358ea","exerciseName":"6","chapterName":"10","chapterTitle":"Making Capital Investment Decisions","groupId":612341,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":341,"solutions":[{"id":6277385,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will assess how depreciation and cash flow are connected to project evaluation","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Depreciation refers to the value of an asset and how much value it loses throughout its lifespan. This is an important aspect since there are many possible causes as to why a certain asset depreciates. In project evaluation, depreciation is a non-cash expense which means that it does not affect cash flow since the \"expenses\" do not involve payments in cash. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"However, the depreciation value should not be ignored when computing the after tax cash flow since it directly affects the tax, and therefore, the cash flow.\n\nA high depreciation value translates to a lower profit for the project which means that the tax rate is also lower. This is why depreciation should not be ignored when solving for the after tax cash flow of a project. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"3f0de70b-8ef6-40a7-9cd5-a944bac33ecd","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3},{"id":6388822,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This question requires us to assess the statement provided in the exercise.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Although depreciation is a non-cash expenditure, it is eligible for deduction on the financial report. Consequently, devaluation reduces tax collected, which is a problematic cash leakage, by such an equivalent amount to the depreciable deflector TCD. \n\nWhereas a lower tax rate is just the same as expected revenue, the implications of the tax-deductible barrier must all be appended to obtain the actual marginal pretax working capital.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"6d36b96e-825c-41c1-ada2-59928e5332ce","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881231,"exerciseName":"7","page":341,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"dc073647-8d25-48fb-ae70-1844da656130","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-10-critical-thinking-questions-7-dc073647-8d25-48fb-ae70-1844da656130"},{"id":14881232,"exerciseName":"8","page":342,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"720e8a56-dc5d-459d-850d-440e619630cc","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-